a) What is the output? 
if (true) { let x = 10; var y = 20; } 
console.log(y); 
console.log(x); 
Explain why?

ans)  Example:- if (true) {
  let x = 10;
  var y = 20;
}

console.log(y); // ?
console.log(x); // ?

Output:- 20
ReferenceError: x is not defined

Why?
var is function-scoped, not block-scoped → so y is accessible outside the if block.

let is block-scoped → x is only valid inside the { } block of the if.
Trying to access it outside gives:

ReferenceError: x is not defined

b) Access the following safely using optional chaining:

const profile = {
  user: {
    details: {
      email: "test@mail.com"
    }
  }
};
Print:

profile.user.details.email
profile.user.details.phone (should not throw error)


ans) const profile = {
  user: {
    details: {
      email: "test@mail.com"
    }
  }
};

Output:- test@mail.com
undefined


c) Create an example where optional chaining prevents a runtime error when accessing a missing nested property.

ans)const data = {
  product: {
    info: null
  }
};

console.log(data.product.info.name); 

Output:-undefined



